spanGrp.span: ‘My aunts’ public hair, they lived here.
Yís migö-wa kö' yugö-wa jie-wa sẽ-lẽ jiska
With their owners [husbands] they came from Talamanca.
Je wakwa ra da-te rö Talamanka wa
Jenẽ ñã jagla-wã Ujarras Jeska í wakwa senã'
A house made out of grass;
Sökkö' wa pe të jũ yuá
there they worked, planting bananas, oranges; they planted beans and corn.
Jeska í shkãblã' chomõ töbiá china töbiá kenĩ ká kwö ká
They fed themselves; they had pigs, hens.
Jie-wa jie-wa ñã chiwã-gẽ kuchi tsõ í wã óshkoro tsõ í wã
later on came the Spaniards and they mixed with them.
jenẽ tögapa sikwa-wa da-te-nẽ jie-wa (_) ñã (_) (_) wötkagá
Other children were born, but they are no longer authentic;
Jenẽ jenẽ ska yabla siga-wa konã-nẽ Ka je rö ditsö' chöglë ĩã kunã
those are the ones living here on the ancestors’ soil.
Jenẽ wakwa jalali-nẽ jiska ñẽ sigeglö-wa je kã' jãrga
They lived on the very source.
